{
  "answer": "**San Hyan Tattvajnana** provides one of the most explicit descriptions, listing the five senses of perception as \"the eye, ear, nose, tongue, and skin\" and distinguishing them from the five senses of action (speech, hands, feet, organ of generation, organ of excretion), while also detailing their corresponding subtle elements (*tanmātra*s) such as sound (*śabdatanmātra*), touch (*sparśatanmātra*), form/color (*rūpatanmātra*), taste (*rasatanmātra*), and smell (*gandhatanmātra*), with experiential explanations.[^1]\n\n**Kalpabuddha** explicitly identifies the five senses (*pañcendriya*) with specific body parts: eyes (*cakṣus*), ears (*śrotra*), nose (*ghrāṇa*), mouth (*jihvā*), and liver (*hṛdaya* or heart), associating each with a Tathāgata deity (Akṣobhya in eyes, Ratnasambhava in ears, etc.).[^2]\n\n**Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana** refers to \"the five senses themselves\" as the \"six enemies\" (likely including mind) that \"poison the body,\" but does not list them individually.[^3]\n\nOther works like **Manusmṛti**, **Paraśara Smṛti**, and **Gaṇapatitattva** discuss sensory restraint or devotion to the senses but lack listings or anatomical descriptions of the senses themselves.[^4]\n\nNo other works in the corpus contain comparably explicit descriptions.\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Tattvajnana*, Chapter 1, [p-d681ce](/works/unknown-san-hyan-tattvajnana-1f29bd/01-chapter-1/translation/#p-d681ce).\n[^2]: *Kalpabuddha*, Chapter 6, [p-c8567e](/works/unknown-kalpabuddha-d760dc/06-chapter-6/translation/#p-c8567e).\n[^3]: *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [p-39472d](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01-chapter-1/translation/#p-39472d).\n[^4]: E.g., *Manusmṛti*, Chapters 1–12 (multiple mentions of sense control, e.g., [p-f2e8ae](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02-chapter-2/translation/#p-f2e8ae)); *Paraśara Smṛti*, Chapter 8, [p-ab1289](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/08-chapter-8/translation/#p-ab1289).",
